            "text": "Multivariate Hybrid SARIMAX-BiLSTM Model for Monthly Rainfall Forecasting Across Heterogeneous Indian States Sanskriti Narain Department of Computer Science and Engineering GD Goenka University Email: sanskritinarain2005@gmail.com Priya Goyal Department of Computer Science and Engineering GD Goenka University Email: priyagupta2k6@gmail.com Abstract-Accurate rainfall prediction is essential for water resource management, agricultural planning, and flood risk mitigation, particularly in climatically heterogeneous regions like India. This paper proposes a residual-based hybrid model combining SARIMAX (Seasonal ARIMA with Exogenous Variables) and BiLSTM (Bi-directional Long Short-Term Memory) for multivariate monthly rainfall prediction across four climatically diverse Indian states: Kerala, Rajasthan, Himachal Pradesh, and Maharashtra. Using 40 years of monthly data (1985-2025) from IMD and ERA5, with temperature and humidity as exogenous covariates, we conduct a systematic ablation study across three model tiers - SARIMA, SARIMAX, and optimized BiLSTM. SARIMAX consistently outperforms both SARIMA and BiLSTM baselines across all states. The proposed hybrid, where BiLSTM models SARIMAX residuals, yields further consistent gains in RMSE (0.87-2.22 mm) and MAE across all four states. Notably, these gains persist even when Ljung-Box tests indicate white-noise residuals, suggesting BiLSTM captures low-level nonlinearities beyond the reach of correlation-based diagnostics. The model generalizes well across diverse rainfall climates without statespecific architectural tuning, though Kerala's highly heterogeneous monsoon dynamics represent a key limitation of monthlyresolution hybrid modeling. Index Terms-Rainfall Forecasting, SARIMAX, Bidirectional LSTM, Hybrid Model, Time Series Forecasting, Exogenous Variables, Monsoon Prediction, India I. INTRODUCTION Forecasting rain is an important part of managing water resources, planning for farming, assessing flo