            "text": "It then trains a BiLSTM on the SARIMAX residuals to learn any remaining non-linear temporal structure. The SARIMAX forecast and the BiLSTM residual correction make up the final forecast. This work's main contributions are as follows: • We create a 40-year monthly multivariate dataset (1985- 2025) for four Indian states by using free geospatial tools to process IMD precipitation NetCDF files and ERA5 reanalysis data in space. • We perform a structured three-tier ablation study to compare SARIMA, SARIMAX, and BiLSTM as separate models, establishing a strong empirical foundation for the hybrid evaluation. • We propose a residual hybrid SARIMAX-BiLSTM architecture and show that it consistently performs better than the SARIMAX baseline in all four states. This is true even though Ljung-Box residual diagnostics show statistically white noise residuals. This demonstrates that deep learning can capture low-level non-linear structures that autocorrelation tests fail to detect. • We offer a state-by-state examination of forecasting challenges, highlighting Kerala's significant monsoon variability (residual standard deviation of 96 mm) as a critical constraint for hybrid architectures utilizing monthly aggregated data, which will influence future research at higher temporal resolutions. II. LITERATURE REVIEW A lot of research has been done on predicting rain, using a variety of methods. These methods can be grouped into four main types: statistical time series models, machine learning approaches, deep learning architectures, and hybrid combinations of these. This section looks at the most important changes in each group and puts the proposed work in the context of what has already been written about it. A. Statistical Approaches Statistical time series models have traditionally constituted the basis for precipitation and hydrological forecasting. Box and Jenkins [1] introduced the Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) family, which is still widely used because it is based on theory, easy to understand, and fast to compute. Seasonal extensions of ARIMA (SARIMA) have been extensively utilised for monthly rainfall series characterised by annual periodicity as a principal structural attribute. Mishra and Desai [2] showed that SARIMA models work well for predicting droughts in India by making accurate seasonal predictions over several months. The SARIMAX extension, which adds outside variables to the seasonal ARIMA framework, has been used to predict rainfall by adding climate indices and weather variables.The Akaike [3] and Schwarz [4] information criteria are now standard tools for choosing the order of SARIMAX, but automated options like the stepwise search procedures used in pmdarima [5]",
